    <h1>A house di&#xAD;vided: Fac&#xAD;tions within Umno POWER BRO&#xAD;KERS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201021/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-21"><time>2020-10-21</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Umno pres­i­dent</p>
    <p>Ah­mad Zahid Hamidi and pre­de­ces­sor Na­jib Razak</p>
    <p>• De­spite be­ing charged with graft, both Na­jib and Zahid re­main widely in­flu­en­tial in the party.</p>
    <p>• They com­mand more than half of the party ’s 39 MPs, mak­ing them ma­jor power bro­kers in Malaysia’s cur­rent po­lit­i­cal im­broglio.</p>
    <p>• Zahid, 67, has ag­i­tated for a shake-up of the gov­ern­ment of Prime Min­is­ter Muhyid­din Yassin, tak­ing ad­van­tage of un­hap­pi­ness within cer­tain sec­tions of the party who have chafed at play­ing sec­ond fid­dle to Tan Sri Muhyid­din’s Parti Pribumi Ber­satu Malaysia.</p>
    <p>• Se­nior lead­ers like Datuk Seri Nazri Aziz and Datuk Seri Ta­jud­din Ab­dul Rah­man have urged Umno to ter­mi­nate its ties with Ber­satu, claim­ing that the Umno grass­roots want this.</p>

